{
  "doc_id": "38496",
  "text": "Molecular imaging-FDG PET typically shows hypometabolism in the frontal and temporal lobes and more severe deficits in the basal ganglia (Figs. 7C and 7D ). These metabolic abnormalities can be identified in patients with HD many years before the onset of clinical symptoms [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Some sources suggest that decreased cortical glucose metabolism is a predictor for more rapid HD progression [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Imaging with less common PET radiotracers such as 11 C-raclopride, a D2 dopamine antagonist, can detect even subtler alterations in basal ganglia function and may be used to prognosticate disease severity and correlate with the number of trinucleotide repeats [CITATION_5] (Figs 7E and 7F) .",
